<br>
Then not too soon afterwards, Hecate came in, and as she touched him in that way many another women had done he shuddered, but kept his composure as she walked off away from him. He watched her and in his head he wondered what she was doing here at the trial. It was open for all to witness but Poseidon did not think anyone ot thing would really come. In any case the heart of the matter grew again in his breast and he turned his attention once more to Hypnos.<br>
<br>
This time he spoke from where he sat, in his authority, and did not let his tongue slip but he did speak what he felt was happening here.<br>
<br>
'You Hypnos, though a lesser god are not a weakling, for even among the Olympians there are some who have been shamed by mortals and lesser immortals alike,' by this he was referring to Ares and he said it in a humorous way but in all seriousness. 'Though I would think you are wise enough to know that there are a great many of the Olympians who's powers are nearly indomitable by others.'<br>
<br>
Poseidon took a breather and thought there was some animosity between to immortals goddessess present who in their own rights were nearly equals, at least in his thought. Then he spoke the truth to Hypnos about the situation at hand.<br>
<br>
&quot;Now sleep god, you are right and wrong you have a defense but have no defense because you as we and you know are guilty of the crimes we have charged you with, and a withstanding punishment will be laid out to you here and now.<br>
Hypnos you are held guilty of the above crimes: 1) Taking your rights to another level, a level that went beyond your rights, such as humiliating or in some way, shape or form seeking to humiliate others by your powers. 2) Being the ring leader of uprising which disturbed or were meant to in any way, shape or form to disturb the peace. 3) And last but not least refusing respect the dignity of your superiors.' He looked on Hypnos sternly and said, 'So how do you plead to these lord Hypnos?'<br>
<br>
